If the native begins with the little finger of the left hand he will call it monou, one

The third finger he naims kai; ane is the conjunction “and,” hence rere kaiane means little finger and the fourth are two fingers and kai added to them they become three fingers.

Morere-morere suggests that these natives are inclined to think in pairs or couples; they certainly do group the fingers into two pairs when they wish to illustrate what they mean by “four.” Taking it that they count thus, morere, one pair, morere-morere, another pair.
